# GVM - Ghidra Version Manager

A command-line utility to install, manage, and update [Ghidra](https://ghidra-sre.org/) versions and extensions.

Supports **Linux**, **macOS**, and **Windows**.

> This is a Python fork of [CUB3D/ghidra-version-manager](https://github.com/CUB3D/ghidra-version-manager) (originally written in Rust).

---

## Installing

### Prerequisites

- **Python 3.11+**
- **JDK 21+** (required by Ghidra 11+) - GVM will check for this and suggest install commands for your platform if missing.

### From source (editable)

```shell
pip install -e .
```

### With notification support

```shell
pip install -e ".[notifications]"
```

---

## Quick Start

```shell
# See what's available
gvm list

# Install the latest Ghidra
gvm install latest

# Launch it
gvm run
```

---

## Usage Guide

In any command that takes a version, you can use:
- A specific tag like `Ghidra_11.4_build`
- `latest` for the most recent release
- `default` for your configured default version

### List available versions

```shell
gvm list
# or
gvm ls
```

Fetches all Ghidra releases from the official NSA GitHub repository.

### Install a version

```shell
gvm install Ghidra_11.4_build
gvm install latest
# or
gvm i latest
```

Downloads and extracts the release. On Linux, a `.desktop` launcher entry is created. On macOS, a `.app` bundle is placed in `/Applications` for Spotlight integration.

### Run Ghidra

```shell
# Launch the default version
gvm run

# Launch a specific version
gvm run Ghidra_11.2_build

# or
gvm r Ghidra_11.2_build
```

If you switch from one version to another, GVM automatically backs up and restores your Ghidra preferences (Linux/macOS).

### Set your default version

```shell
gvm default set Ghidra_11.4_build
gvm default show
```

Setting a default lets you run `gvm run` without specifying a version every time.

### Update to the latest version

```shell
gvm update
# or
gvm u
```

Downloads and installs the latest release. Your preferences are automatically migrated.

### Check for updates

```shell
gvm check-update
# or
gvm U
```

Forces an update check against the GitHub API and displays the latest available version.

### Uninstall a version

```shell
gvm uninstall Ghidra_11.4_build
# or
gvm del Ghidra_11.4_build
```

### Locate an installation on disk

```shell
gvm locate
gvm locate Ghidra_11.4_build
```

Prints the filesystem path to the specified (or default) Ghidra installation.

### Preferences

```shell
# Show current preferences
gvm prefs show
# or
gvm p show

# Enable PyGhidra launcher
gvm prefs set py3 true

# Override UI scale (useful for HiDPI displays)
gvm prefs set scale 2

# Set a custom install directory
gvm prefs set install_dir D:\Ghidra

# Reset back to the default install directory
gvm prefs set install_dir default
```

| Preference | Values | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `py3` | `true` / `false` | Use PyGhidra runner instead of the standard launcher |
| `scale` | integer | Override the UI scale factor in `launch.properties` |
| `install_dir` | path / `default` | Directory where Ghidra versions are installed. Set to `default` to reset |

### Preferences backup and restore (Linux/macOS)

```shell
# Back up preferences for the default version
gvm settings backup my_prefs.zip

# Back up a specific version's preferences
gvm settings backup my_prefs.zip Ghidra_11.4_build

# Restore preferences
gvm settings restore my_prefs.zip
gvm settings restore my_prefs.zip Ghidra_11.4_build
```

Preferences are stored as ZIP archives containing the Ghidra preferences file and a GVM metadata config.

### Extensions

GVM ships with a built-in registry of 27 third-party extensions.

```shell
# List all known extensions
gvm extensions list
# or
gvm e ls

# Install an extension to the default Ghidra version
gvm extensions install FindCrypt

# Install to a specific version
gvm extensions install PDK Ghidra_11.4_build

# Uninstall an extension
gvm extensions uninstall FindCrypt
# or
gvm e rm FindCrypt
```

#### Available extensions

**Processor Architectures (19):** 4004, Allegrex, Alpha, Amiga, C166, CSKY, EFI, Hexagon, iRISC, M16C, MCORE, nanoMIPS, niosII, PDK, PicoBlaze, RL78, RX, Score7, STM-8

**Exporters (2):** BinExport, Delinker

**Loaders (3):** DTB, NTR, XBE

**Tools (3):** AssistMCP, FindCrypt, Markdown Notepad

Extensions are either downloaded as release assets (manual install via Ghidra UI) or cloned and extracted as processor modules, depending on their type.

### Global flags

| Flag | Description |
|---|---|
| `-v`, `--verbose` | Enable detailed logging output |
| `-o`, `--offline` | Disable all network access (use cached data only) |
| `-l`, `--launcher` | Run in launcher mode |

---

## Configuration

GVM stores its state in a `cache.toml` file:

| Platform | Path |
|---|---|
| Windows | `%LOCALAPPDATA%\gvm\cache.toml` |
| Linux / macOS | `~/.local/opt/gvm/cache.toml` |

This file tracks installed versions, extensions, preferences, default version, and update-check timestamps. It is managed automatically by GVM.

---

## Platform behavior

| Feature | Windows | macOS | Linux |
|---|---|---|---|
| Install path | `%LOCALAPPDATA%\gvm\` | `~/.local/opt/gvm/` | `~/.local/opt/gvm/` |
| Desktop launcher | -- | `.app` in `/Applications` | `.desktop` file |
| Preferences backup/restore | Not supported | Supported | Supported |
| Ghidra runner | `ghidraRun.bat` | `ghidraRun` | `ghidraRun` |
| PyGhidra runner | `support/pyghidraRun.bat` | `support/pyghidraRun` | `support/pyghidraRun` |

---

## Feature parity with the original Rust version

This Python fork is a **complete port** of the original [CUB3D/ghidra-version-manager](https://github.com/CUB3D/ghidra-version-manager) Rust implementation.

| Feature | Rust (original) | Python (this fork) |
|---|---|---|
| Install / uninstall versions | Yes | Yes |
| Run Ghidra | Yes | Yes |
| Default version management | Yes | Yes |
| Update to latest | Yes | Yes |
| Check for updates | Yes | Yes |
| List available releases | Yes | Yes |
| Locate installation path | Yes | Yes |
| Extension management (install/uninstall/list) | Yes | Yes |
| Built-in extension registry (27 extensions) | Yes | Yes |
| Preferences (PyGhidra, UI scale) | Yes | Yes |
| Preferences backup/restore (Linux/macOS) | Yes | Yes |
| Auto-migrate preferences on version switch | Yes | Yes |
| Desktop notifications (optional) | Yes | Yes |
| Linux `.desktop` launcher | Yes | Yes |
| macOS `.app` launcher | Yes | Yes |
| JDK detection and install guidance | Yes | Yes |
| Offline mode | Yes | Yes |
| Verbose mode | Yes | Yes |
| TOML-based cache | Yes | Yes |
| Download progress bar | Yes | Yes |
| Command aliases (`ls`, `i`, `r`, `del`, etc.) | Yes | Yes |
| Windows desktop launcher creation | No | No |

**Differences:**
- **No compiled binary** - runs as a Python package via `pip install` instead of `cargo install`
- **Fewer system dependencies** - no Rust toolchain required; just Python 3.11+
- **`plyer` replaces `notify-rust`** for desktop notifications (optional dependency)

